Lipid droplets were localized and initially linked using the TrackMate plugin in Fiji. Spot detection was performed using a Laplacian-of-Gaussian (LoG) detector on PHYSIQ-denoised volumetric SRS images. The estimated LD diameter was set according to the apparent LD size in the denoised volumes, and the detection threshold was adjusted to retain visually identifiable LDs while suppressing background noise. The maximum linking distance was selected based on the maximum physically plausible LD displacement between consecutive volumetric frames, estimated from the expected upper bound of LD velocity and the inter-volume time interval. Specifically, the allowed linking distance was chosen to be larger than the typical frame-to-frame displacement of LDs but small enough to avoid linking spatially unrelated droplets.

The resulting TrackMate trajectories were exported and further analyzed using custom MATLAB scripts. For each trajectory, we calculated the frame-to-frame displacement, total trajectory length, average velocity, maximum displacement and directionality. Mean-squared displacement (MSD) curves were computed as a function of lag time. The anomalous diffusion exponent α was estimated by fitting the short-lag MSD curve in log-log space. Trajectories were classified as confined, Brownian-like or directed motion according to the fitted α value.
